  -*- Mode: Text;  -*-
*************************************************************************
* This text contains the differences between the currently released	*
* version of sck, the Sather-K - Compiler of Karlsruhe, and the latest	*
* release of the Sather-K - language description comming with this	*
* release.								*
* Author: Peter Holzwarth (holzw@info.uni-karlsruhe.de)			*
* Copyright 1994 (C) Peter Holzwarth					*
*************************************************************************
 
 
*************************
* Major differences:	*
* ==================	*
*************************
 
Overloading of routines:
------------------------
Overloading of routines is not implemented in this release of sck. The
overloading features are currently being debugged. A new release of
sck comming up in the second half of December 1994 will contain
overloading.
 
Operator functions:
-------------------
Operator functions are not implemented in this release of sck. The
operator functions are currently being debugged. A new release of
sck comming up in the second half of December 1994 will contain
operator functions.
 
External language interface:
----------------------------
The external language interface of sck is implemented by classes
declared via the special class name "C". Class declarations for these
classes can appear more than once within the source text. In this case
all declarations of all classes "C" are merged together by the
compiler. "C" classes can declare routines and shared and const
attributes. These routines and attributes must be supplied by other
modules that are linked together with the module generated by
sck. Other modules can use Sather-K routines and objects under names
that can be defined in a file named like the main class of a Sather-K
program with the extension .sather. Examples of such files can be
found in the libraries.
 
Bound Streams:
--------------
Bound streams are currently not implemented in sck.
 
 
 
*************************
* Minor differences:	*
* ==================	*
*************************
 
The minor differences between sck and the language definition of
Sather-K together with informations about implementation specific 
details about sck are listed by paragraph numbers of the language 
definition.
 
 
3.1:	There are no special letters allowed in names of types,
----	variables and attributes.
 
	Type names may contain lowercase characters as well as
	uppercase characters. E.g. "int500" may be a valid type.
 
3.3:	There are currently no UNIVERSAL_... types implemented in sck.
----
	Chars are of type CHAR. They are currently 8 bits wide, but
	this may change without notice. Use the library functions to
	convert between Sathter-K chars and those of C or other
	programming languages.
 
4:	The file sys_dot_sather contains a list of library files that
--	must be included in any compilation of a Sather-K program.
	The file <ROOTCLASS_NAME>.sather contains all source files
	that the user wants to be included while compiling his
	project.
 
4.3:	If Stars are used within constructors then each star is replaced
----	by the value 1.
	The declaration
	
	a: #A[10,*,1,*];
	
	is a shortcut for
	
	a: A[10,*,1,*]:= #A[10,1,1,1];
 
 
4.4:	"is_equal" is commutative in the following way:
----	If one side of a comparison is void (e.g.: void = "my String")
	then the type of the other side is used to determine the class
	in which the feature "is_equal" is searched.
	If the left and the right hand side of a comparison are of
	different types the following rules apply:
	 1) If the user has not overwritten "is_equal" in the type of the
	 left hand side then the comparison yields false.
	 2) Else the result depends on the user defined function in the
	 type of the left hand side.
 
5.1:	It is an error to use a type name that is defined as a class
----	name elsewhere in the program text as a type parameter name.
 
5.2:	Attributes and variables with a value type and no explicit
----	initialisation are initialized by constructing an object of
	their type. If the type of an attribute or variable is a
	polymorphic type $T then an object of type T is constructed.
 
	If an entity with value type is declared constant then also its
	attributes and in case of array types its array elements are
	constant.
 
6.8:	The syntax of exception statements differs between sck and the
----	language definition. For sck an exception statement has the
	following syntax:
 
	'begin' block 'except' IDENTIFIER [exceptwhen_part]* [else_part] 'end' .
 
	exceptwhen_part ->  'when' typelist 'then' block .
	else_part	->  'else' block .
 
	The "exceptwhen_part" is optional and can be repeated.
	The "else_part" is optional.
 
	Exception names differ from the ones in the language definition.
	The following table lists the different names
	
	Sather-K			sck
	----------------------------------------------------------------
	FLOAT_OVERFLOW			EXCEPTION_FPE
	FLOAT_UNDERFLOW			EXCEPTION_FPE
	INTEGER_OVERFLOW		EXCEPTION_INT
	ZERO_DEVIDE			EXCEPTION_FPE
	INDEX_ERROR			EXCEPTION_ARRAY1_BOUND
	REFERENCE_ERROR			EXCEPTION_VOID
	PRE_ERROR			EXCEPTION_PRE
	POST_ERROR			EXCEPTION_POST
	INVARIANT_ERROR			EXCEPTION_INV
	STREAM_TERMINATION		-
	EXIT				-
	NUMERIC_ERROR			EXCEPTION_FPE
 
7.2:	Routines without parameters may be overloaded by routinens with
----	parameters.
 
	Overloading is resolved as follows:
	1) sck searches for a routine with parameters exactly matching
	   those of the applied occurence of the routine.
	2) If no routine with exactly matching parameters is found, sck
	   searches for a routine with coercible parameters.
	Actual parameters that are preceeded by a type cast must always
	match exactly.
 
8.1:	There is no routine "init" with a predefined meaning in sck.
----	If you want to initialize a new object and cannot do this by
	using a constructor, you must explicitly call an init function.
 
8.2:	There is no class "TEXT" in the library of sck. Instead we have
----	the classes "IN", "OUT" and "ERR" for providing input and output
	to files and the console.
 
8.2.1:	For the statements
------
	a: A[10,*];
	a:= b;
	
	sck generates code that checks if the first index attribute of
	the object contained in b is less or equal than 10. In case of b
	being of type ARRAY[*,*](T) this means that the first dimension
	of the array in b may not be larger than 10.
 
	The following types are currently not implemented in sck:
	BITS[*], BIT, BYTE, SHORT_INT, LONG_INT, UNSIGNED,
	SHORT_UNSIGNED, LONG_UNSIGNED, FLTE, FLTDE, INTINF.
 
9.1.2:	The beginning of this text includes a short description of the
------	class C which is used as the foreign language interface for sck.
 

